events.name: Sesame Street Live! Make Your Magic
events.info: When magician extraordinaire Justin visits Sesame Street to put on a magic show for the whole neighborhood, Elmo wants to be part of the big event. But there's one problem…Elmo doesn't know how to do magic! That's when Elmo teams up with Abby and Justin, embarking on an amazing journey where Elmo will discover the "power of yet" -the lesson that with perseverance and practice, nothing can stand between you and your dream. Along the way, Elmo and Abby, joined by their friends Cookie Monster, Big Bird, Grover, Rosita, Count von Count, and Gonger, discover the many magical moments in everyday life. In the end, Elmo learns that you can do anything you set your mind to if you just keep trying! Join your favorite Sesame Street friends on this magical adventure when Sesame Street Live! Make Your Magic comes to your neighborhood *Note: Costumes not permitted for guests 14 years & older.

venues.accessibleSeatingDetail: The wheelchair/accessible seats are on the outside aisle of sections A and D on the main floor and row HH in the same sections. It is always seat 1 in section A and the higher numbered seat in section D on the outside aisle. These are theatre seats and must be unbolted and removed for a wheelchair. Accessible aisle seat is the even X-number, the companion is the odd X-number. If you are selling into an account, please indicate in the Extra line to keep or remove the seat. Row HH is 6 moveable, padded chairs and a wheelchair can sit anywhere along the row.

events.name: Umphrey's McGee
events.info: Tickets available locally at Ranch Records.The music of Umphreys McGee unfolds like an unpredictable conversation between longtime friends. Its six participantsBrendan Bayliss [guitar, vocals], Jake Cinninger [guitar, vocals], Joel Cummins [keyboards, piano, vocals], Andy Farag [percussion], Kris Myers [drums, vocals], and Ryan Stasik [bass]know just how to communicate with each other on stage and in the studio. A call of progressive guitar wizardry might elicit a response of soft acoustic balladry, or a funk groove could be answered by explosive percussion. At any moment, heavy guitars can give way to heavier blues as the boys uncover the elusive nexus between jaw-dropping instrumental virtuosity and airtight songcraft.

events.name: CURREN$Y: The Hot August Nights Forever West Coast Tour and Smokey Charles
events.info: The VIP ticket allows the ticket holder to skip to the front of the line and also allows for access to the private balcony upstairs.Born Shante Anthony Franklin and raised in New Orleans, Curren$y was originally signed to Master Ps No Limit label, but in 2005 he made the move to Lil Wayne and Birdmans Cash Money imprint, Young Money. He appeared on Waynes Tha Carter II album that same year, then in 2006, Curren$ys Where da Cash At single was released -- both on its own and as part of Waynes Dedication 2 mixtape -- but a promised album never materialized. Not one to sit idle, Curren$y started Fly Society with professional skateboarder Terry Kennedy in 2007. The brand was originally planned as a line of apparel, but evolved into a music label as the rappers relationship with Young Money soured. After leaving the label at the end of 2007 with Fly Society in tow, a series of underground mixtapes appeared before Curren$y hooked up with the digital-only Amalgam Digital for the early 2009 release This Aint No Mixtape. The relationship continued that October with the download-only Jet Files, but in early 2010 he joined the Def Jam family via Damon Dashs DD172 imprint. With the labels in-house producer Ski Beatz handling most of the production on both, Curren$ys Pilot Talk album appeared in July of that year, with Pilot Talk II landing in 2010. The stopgap release Weekend at Burnies followed in 2011, with the retro backing tracks coming from producer Monsta Beatz. Beatz, along with the J.U.S.T.I.C.E. Leauge and Pharrell, was back for the rappers 2012 street release, The Stone Immaculate. ~ David Jeffries

Infared hearing devices are available at the coat check. A security deposit (drivers license) is required. For hearing impaired assistance call the PCPA at 503-248-4335.

generalInfo.generalRule: No flash cameras allowed inside. No recording devices allowed inside. No smoking inside building. Binoculars are allowed. Latecomers must wait in lobby to be seated by an usher during a convenient pause in the performance.
generalInfo.childRule: Children under 1 are usually free, but must sit on a ticketholders lap. This policy may vary depending on the event and the event promoter. *** For all Portland Opera and Broadway Across America shows everyone is required to have a ticket for entry! ***

ada.adaCustomCopy: Accessible seating for events at the Keller Auditorium is available on the purchase page. Select the ADA icon to view available seats.
ada.adaHours: The Keller Auditorium Box Office is open 2 hours prior to event starting time.  Advance tickets are available through www.ticketmaster.com and Charge-By-Phone 800-877-7575.

venues.name: Arlene Schnitzer Concert Hall

boxOfficeInfo.phoneNumberDetail: Portland Center for the Performing Arts Business Office: 503-248-4335 Weather Related Info: 503-274-6592 TDD: 503-796-9342 (box office) 503-796-0122 (business office)
boxOfficeInfo.openHoursDetail: The Arlene Schnitzer box office opens 2 hours prior to the performance. Advance tickets are available through www.ticketmaster.com, Charge-By-Phone (503)224-4400 or at local Ticketmaster outlets.
boxOfficeInfo.acceptedPaymentDetail: The Arlene Schnitzer box office accepts cash and check (with check guarantee card). Visa and Mastercard are also accepted for most events.
boxOfficeInfo.willCallDetail: Will call opens 2 hours prior to the performance.

venues.parkingDetail: Pay parking is available on 6th St. Other lots within a 2 block radius. There is a parking structure in the Broadway Building across the street and surface lots on SW 10th and Main. Public: 3 blocks from the Pioneer Square MAX stop. Rules/Regulations: Most touring shows do not allow reentry if someone leaves the building.
venues.accessibleSeatingDetail: The wheelchair/accessible seats are on the outside aisle of sections A and D on the main floor and row HH in the same sections. It is always seat 1 in section A and the higher numbered seat in section D on the outside aisle. These are theatre seats and must be unbolted and removed for a wheelchair. Accessible aisle seat is the even X-number, the companion is the odd X-number. If you are selling into an account, please indicate in the Extra line to keep or remove the seat. Row HH is 6 moveable, padded chairs and a wheelchair can sit anywhere along the row.
